abstract = {The spleen fulfills fundamental roles in both Hematological and Immunological processes, serving as the largest lymphoid organ within the body. Despite its significance, the spleen remains relatively understudied compared to other solid organs. Recent years have brought to light the profound implications of complete splenic absence, typically resulting from splenectomy or hypofunction, in various disease states including sickle cell anemia, cancer, and HIV infection. Diminished splenic activity often predisposes individuals to thromboembolic events and immune deficiencies, as exemplified by clinical manifestations observed in cases of COVID-19 where splenic dysfunction has been documented. Experimental models of SARS-CoV-2 infection have revealed clinical lymphopenia and splenic atrophy. This chapter consolidates current insights into the spleen's role in Regenerative Medicine, presenting novel perspectives for interdisciplinary research encompassing in vitro disease modeling, drug screening, and therapeutic interventions, alongside its traditional applications in hematology and immunology. Remarkable advancements have characterized spleen regenerative medicine in the 21st century: (a) pioneering the development of artificial spleen devices; (b) identifying a diverse array of pluripotent adult stem cells within the organ's stroma; (c) elucidating its contribution to the regeneration of insulin-producing cells within pancreatic islets; (d) unraveling mechanisms governing splenic regeneration; (e) showcasing its diagnostic utility in assessing immunotoxicity to biomaterials; (f) exploiting its therapeutic potential in ischemic stroke treatment; (g) demonstrating its capacity to support hematopoiesis and myelopoiesis; (h) devising protocols for generating splenic organoids adaptable for diverse applications; and (i) engineering biological scaffolds from decellularized splenic extracellular matrix, facilitating the development of hepatic, pancreatic, splenic